I think it’s a general sentiment that Henry and I share, but I’ll try my best to sum up the reasons that he does for me.

The first is the UG vs. RW dilemma for EDH. That’s an overarching annoyance for me, already. I really love design (tried my hand at GDS3, read all design articles, etc), and to see those colors side-by-side do the same things over and over again... it’s frustrating from that design aspect.
10/15 available Simic generals arguably fall into this archetype, and I think 12-14/20 Boros falls into it. And I’m being generous to Boros.
It feeds into itself more so because the typical RW attack everywhere is a fairly “weak” archetype where UG’s “draw cards for value” is generically powerful.

Next is the “leaves the battlefield” bit. It makes Toothy easier to use unlike Elenda... but a lot more abusable. There is no counter play. Once toothy gets counters... you WILL draw cards, outside of some cornercase thief of blood interaction/ hex parasite lock... 
I think that’s the most egregious thing about toothy.

It’s obviously geared for Commander which is fine, but I have a deep-seated and personal gripe that Wizards tends to only fix effects once they go blue OR they push effects first time effects blue over the edge... and just general bleed that feels more egregious. This is a personal bias though, and I’ll relent on this more than other.

This is the biggest stretch of an annoyance, but WHY, WHY, are the UG Pairs 3 and 4 CMC???
Toothy could be 6 mana and it’d still be great.
For example, the other partner pair costs:
UR (5,5)
GB (3,4)
UR Twins (6,6)
RW (3,6)
BW (5,6)
Comparing them to their contemporaries... Toothy comes off as even more under-costed considering the others are overcosted (looking at you Krav and Regna.) That’s ignoring the fact it’s a G/x partner so ramping isn’t an issue.

I’m sure there’s a few smaller gripes, but I think these are the main ones.

That's the other half of this, though. Both RW and UG are stuck in a design cul-de-sac at WotC. RW just gets 'anything to do with the combat phase' and UG get value engines that reward you for doing what you normally do in a game, except actually win. That's really why I hate the fact that Lab Man exists - it's a cop out solution to the fact that so many UG decks merely build engines that draw cards but don't actually move the game towards closure. 

Lab Man rewards blue decks for bad deck building.

What grinds my gears about Toothy is, they naturally added 'leaves the battlefield' so it plays in EDH; however, they could easily have made it 'dies or is put into the command zone'. Normally they won't reference the cz in a standard-legal product; however, this is a supplemental product that already has planeswalkers with the text 'can be your commander'.
